< date>
1613673838277</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
I'm a veterinary technician. I came in from out of state to take care of my father and his dog while he is in the hospital in critical condition. I was totally unaware of the fact that his dog was in congestive heart failure and had not been receiving the proper treatment for two years. When I realized she was in CHF I got in touch with her vet. Despite the fact that they did not have any appointments open they were able to fit me in as a walk-in the very next day. I had to wait a short time because I was not on the schedule - which is more than reasonable - but they kept me up to date and were very kind, understanding and professional. When a slot opened up to see my father's dog they took her back, examined her and the doctor came out to the car to talk with me about her condition. They did exactly the care I wanted, gave her the medication that she needed and provided me with all of the information and paperwork I might need to take her back to Florida with me if I need to in the event that my father is unable to care for her. The staff was extremely gracious and sweet, especially the receptionist, Brenda, who listened to my concerns and made every conceivable effort to help me with the situation. They were completely understanding of the fact that I was not on my father's account but needed to see to her care anyway in the state of emergency that I found myself. With everything in my life swirling out of control right now because of my father's illness it was such a relief to have something I needed go so easily. Thank you to everyone at Ohana for this experience. Being in the field myself I know the effort it takes to accommodate walk-ins, particularly right now during the pandemic. Stay well, make sure you all remember to self-care and resist compassion fatigue and remember that you are appreciated.<//review>

< review>
We needed to get in touch with Ohana as quickly as possible for my father-in-law's dog, who has come to this clinic for years. Ohana responded to the pressing need immediately, helping us arrange a time to come in the next morning, despite their full schedule of appointments. I know how hard it is to work someone in, particularly with the extra burdens that covid-19 has placed on every business. Ohana went the extra mile to help us and take care of my father-in-law's dog. We had a short wait that was unavoidable given everything that they were dealing with at the time. They provided friendly, pleasant customer service to us, and compassionate care for the patient. It was clear that Ohana's staff and doctor cared about both clients and patients. I'd like to make a special shout-out to Brenda for helping us, and thank everyone involved in Amelia's care.<//review>

< Text>
Covid-19 really has made many companies adjust their policies and procedures, Ohana unfortunately has not made the transition very easy on pets and owners.
I had scheduled my dog Nirvana for an annual exam last month. Scheduling was per normal process, no notification of covid procedure changes were advised. This morning I proceed to clinic and arrived at 10:40 for an 11am appt, however no parking was available, so I made three attempts as I had a few minutes to spare. Unfortunately no parking ever opened up so I parked maybe a 5 min walk away and proceeded to the clinic on foot. On arrival, i noticed the door had a notice advising we must remain in our vehicles and phone in. I phoned in, advised the staff I was unable to remain in vehicle as I had to walk up do to no parking and was standing outside in the 87 degree sun (no shaded area nor outdoor seating availavle) i waited 10 minutes for a staff member to come and meet me outside and informed me I would not be able to enter with my dog, however I could wait inside at about a 20 foot distance from the front desk. I kept my hands to myself never took a seat and kept my mask on. Once my dog was out of sight another staff member advised I would not be able to wait inside due covid, I told them I understood however no seating nor shaded area was available. They suggested I park in an unofficial parking spot which required me to drive over the sidewalk, I said I couldn't as I have a very low car. They suggested I block other vehicles, which would require me to back out and in to allow other vehicles to exit. They continued with I could not wait inside. At this point I became frustrated with the obsurd solutions, and simply took my dog and left the establishment.
It was a simple situation made difficult, many establishments have adjusted to outdoor shading and seating. Maybe even a phone call 30 min prior to arrival advising of the business schedule and possibly rescheduling prior to causing clients and pets inconveniences. My visit was not an emergency, and would have understood why they needed to reschedule. Simple solutions, before a problem arises would have been great. Expecting clients to wait outside in the blistering sun, offroad on the sidewalk and risk vehicle damage and block in cars. That's just unrealistic, please send all clients a notice of challenges and inconveniences prior to arrival it will allow us all to better prepare and make necessary arrangements.
All, please pack and umbrella, water and portable chair (if unable to stand too long), as parking may not be available.<//Text>

I work just a few blocks from Doral's, after driving by it every day for years, I decided to start getting my Nissan serviced there at 25,000 miles. 75,000 miles later, the only work they've recommended is the recommended maintenance from the manufacturer. <rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Austin did an excellent job with this unusual transaction. I live out of state which made the process of looking at the car, talking about options and rebates, etc., and, most of all, taking delivery somewhat challenging. Austin made it clear that he was there to make this a great experience for me (I hate buying cars).

And he did!

We talked many times about the options available and those with which I was interested. He knew the car very well, which I truly appreciate (way too many clueless salesmen over the years that had no idea what they were trying to sell me). He was always quick to get back to me when I had a question (there were many), and when he had to do research to answer it, he jumped in with both feet and presented an answer thorough that he often preempted my next one.

When we had finally put together the car I wanted we did zero haggling over the price. I had done a little homework and when Austin gave me his price I immediately knew Steves had offered me a GREAT DEAL!

The final stroke was Austin driving the car from dealership to my house near Portland, Oregon!

Flash forward to today: I am loving my new Tahoe! I have driven a Tahoes and Suburbans before, but this new model is, by far, my favorite. And I would recommend, without hesitation, Steves to anyone I know.</Review>

<username>Mike Stearns<//username><Response>None< /Response>< date>
1495209199564</date>
<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOmqXxamVf0ELmZ1njLCqXyAX-2DID5KSs41R_b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics><Text>I tried my very first massage chair recently while returning home from a business trip, waiting on a flight at the Nashville airport. Between intermittent sciatica flare-ups during my trip and lugging heavy bags through the airport, my back was aching, and I thought I'd give it a try. Although this chair had no leg and foot massagers, I found that five dollars on my debit card provided relief. I decided I wanted one of these for my own.

After reading a number of online reviews of different makes and models and watching several YouTube videos as well, I found a massage chair showroom at a store called "Relax the Back" in the Kansas city area. I decided I wanted to take some chairs for a "test drive" before buying. The sales people there were friendly enough but not very knowledgeable. But I did get demos in the Human Touch Nova, the Inada DreamWave and a third chair from Chinese maker, Cozzia. Out of the three, I liked the DreamWave the best. But it lacked foot rollers. The Nova looked weird (kind of like Spock's coffin in Star Trek) and the Cozzia just felt cheap. It creaked and groaned like it was trying to self-destruct.

I wasn't very impressed with the staff at this store, so I decided to investigate retailers online. Massage Chair Relief kept coming up over and over again. Dr. Weidner's online videos were informative and seemed to be objective. And the company received consistently glowing reviews from customers I decided to give their toll free number a call. The phone was answered by Michael Nguyen who manages the showroom in Cerritos, CA. Michael was patient, knowledgeable and polite. He listened to what my needs were and offered several selections. He suggested the Luraco iRobotics i7 chair because it had the equivalent build quality and reliability ofthe DreamWave and offered additional features like foot rollers, the ability to save user profiles, a more robust and contemporary Linux-based smartphone-like remote and a build/support network right here in the good ol' US of A. He mentioned that their factory was located in Arlington, TX.

Well, it just so happened I was travelling to the DFW area on business. I called Michael and asked if he could arrange a tour of Luraco's facility and a demo of their chair. He was able to set up an appointment that afternoon. I was greeted by two very friendly employees at Luraco who gave my 88-year-old mother and me a tour of the facility. (I was staying at mom's because she lives in the area and my company likes it when I save hotel costs. Mom likes it too.) The building was impeccably clean. The front office section was tiled in marble. That led into the manufacturing, assembly and quality control sections of the building. Also stunningly clean and well organized. Toward the back was a showroom. Along the way, we were greeted with a friendly "hello" and handshake by several smiling employees. I could tell they enjoyed their jobs and were proud of their products. I spent the next half hour in an i7 chair, experiencing the most wonderful massage I ever had, second only to human hands.

After thanking my gracious hosts, I left the facility, called Michael and ordered my chair. I was able to take advantage of a special sale that had just been announced and took advantage of the "White Glove" delivery service. The chair was delivered on time, expertly set up in my media room downstairs and I couldn't be more pleased. As an additional surprise, Dr. Weidner sent me a box of candies and chocolates, a coffee mug and hot chocolate...all to enjoy in my new chair. I've set up and saved a user profile for myself and have used the chair now for the past couple of days. I have to say, I couldn't be more pleased.

Thanks to the folks at Luraco, Dr. Weidner, Michael Nguyen and the delivery service for a second-to-none experience in customer service and quality</Text>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
Our chiropractor has a massage chair in his waiting room, and it kind of got us hooked. But in deciding what to purchase, we were overwhelmed with the number of choices and the conflicting information about their features and qualities. Some of the reviews that compare chairs give -- we learned the hard way -- positive reviews to massage chair companies for a fee. After buying a chair online that we wound up returning because of this misleading advertising, we found Alan Weidner's blog, which provides careful, unbiased, and thorough research into the industry's best chairs. We called his Southern California store and a smart and enthusiastic man named Michael Nguyen spent nearly an hour talking with us on the phone about all the information and misinformation we had gathered, sharing a wealth of knowledge. He encouraged us to make the 2 hour trip to the store, which we did. We chose the chair we thought we would buy based on our discussions with Michael, but we chose it with more confidence after having compared it to other top-of-the-line chairs we were able to test drive in the store. This was a big investment for us, but the chair, Infinity's IT8500, is a dream! In some ways it is better than having our own personal masseuse (and we are both in the health care field so are quite particular). It gives a deep massage, so if that is not what you want, this is not the chair for you, but it gives you many options about how that massage will be delivered. We ran into one design complaint and Michael went to the manufacturer and found that the feature we didn't like could be disabled (that the chair returns to sitting position when it has finished a program). So this chair is just perfect for us. We are very happy with it and recommend it highly.</Review>

I've been wanting a high-end massage chair for years and this year I could finally afford one. I did research online and found Dr Weidner's youtube vids, then discovered they had a store around LA where I live.  They carry another expensive chair from Luraco so I figured I'd better go try it out.  I went to the store thinking I would just try that chair out since the rest were made in China and less expensive, I figured they weren't as good.
I met Michael, the store manager, and he really educated me about the massage chairs.  I ended up spending 3 hours trying different ones.  He explained that it's not about the cost of the massage chair, because they carry the best Chinese chairs, it's about what suits you best.
I ended up buying the Ogawa Smart 3D chair, which I am totally in love with - I use it everyday!  It hits all the right places for me and is a very comfortable chair to sit in.  I'm a big guy with broad shoulders and my wife is petite, because the Ogawa has adjustable sides it fits us both nicely.  I also love the Ogawa's remote, it an app on a Samsung Galaxy tablet which comes with the chair.  The app has 17 awesome preprogramed massages, manual settings, and you can even have a custom massage just for you.  The Upper Back and Thai massage are my favorites.  If you carry tension in your neck and shoulders, you should try this chair.
I highly recommend buying from Massage Chair Relief as they really stand behind their products and have excellent customer service.  No one else gives a 90 day satisfaction guarantee return policy and a lifetime labor warranty just for buying from them.  Plus I've never met anyone more knowledgeable about massage chairs, nor any store with so many to try.  They're the best!!</text>

< rating>

<Text>I've had the Luraco I7 a few weeks now, and feel I can give an informative review. First, I am obsessive about researching products. I found 75% of the valuable material on the web regarding massage chairs came directly from Dr. Weidner. The interviews, articles, reviews, videos, etc... I felt they earned my business simply by providing all that information. Once I engaged Massage-Chair-Relief directly to discuss purchasing a chair it was a no brainer. Best price, best warrantee, best service and responsiveness I could imagine. Where you buy is the most important thing you can research, which is why I put this part on the top and you can skip the rest of my wordy review.

I live about 1000 miles from their Southern California showroom, and decided to take them up on their out-of-stater discount to offset a visit. I flew out in the morning to Long Beach airport, and was greeted by Michael. It's maybe 15 minutes to the showroom, and he drove me back later that day after stopping for some food. I got to try out everything I had read about. I highly recommend doing this if you can, but I have some advice. Make sure you know what you definitely want to try out down to the body part. You need to prioritize what you want to see within the first hour or so. Also, once you see how strong it CAN be, tone it back. After about 90 minutes it will become painful if your body isn't used to a massage chair. So for critical comparisons, make sure you get them in before you're TOO massaged. I spent 4 hours there and was sore for two days afterwards :).

I went to compare the Luraco, Panasonic, and Dreamwave. My issues were upper back (nerve pain down the arm), traps, calves, IT bands. I didn't expect any miracles on the last two, but was hopeful. I found each massage chair has something better than the others. I really loved the Panasonic heated 4 head rollers, and how they dug into my traps. The Dreamwave has killer airbags. You don't even need to use rollers if you just want to light massage. They also have things that are much worse than the others. The Panasonic was very uncomfortable on my feet. There's a single nodule that pokes into the wrong part of my foot and is a bit painful. The Dreamwave remote was not intuitive at all, and I read it was best for IT Bands but I wasn't feeling it. The Luraco turned out to dig into the traps nearly as well as the Panasonic, the feet are enjoyable. The big surprise to me was the IT Bands. They REALLY dug in when I turned up the intensity and used the manual mode to swivel my hips into the airbags. It was somewhat unpleasant, but in a good way. Working IT Bands is never pleasant when it's happening :). The calves were better in my opinion, but nothing seems to really work the calves. Even the chairs with rollers for the calves didn't dig in like you'd hope. The final selling point was the superior technology. Memory settings (no scanning waits), intuitive remote, intensity adjustments to 4 discrete sections.

The black color looks better than I imagined. It's very quiet. It's easy enough to operate I don't have to "train" anyone on how to try it out. The massage is wonderful, especially in the neck. It gives some light traction and works the base of the skull. The shoulders are great, and I really enjoy the IT Bands. The remote and technology allow you to skip user scanning every time, and I couldn't imagine feeling more confident in where I purchased from. 5 Star Chair, 10 Star company.</Text>< Pics>

We bought the Osaki Pro Summit massage chair almost a month ago. It was a big decision for us, what machine we going to choose. We live in Florida, so the only chance to try out a machine was the Brookstone massage chair( which is alright). We were looking for in the 5000$ price range. I called first Dr. Weidner, to asked his opinion about the chairs. Then I spoke to Michael from the CA store, who gave us the outmost help that a customer representative can give. We talked hours for almost 2 weeks, when a made my final decision on the Summit.
The chair is absolutely a amazing! The foot rollers are perfect and strong, you can modify your foot position so rollers are hitting more areas on your sole. Neck and back massage also does a great job after a long day. Air pumps can really squeeze your extremities for better circulation. With manual programs you can target specific areas( spot massage) on your back and change the width in 3 positions(rolling).
To put together the chair was easy (20 minutes).
Overall the chair does not compete with a human massage therapist's hand, but trust me, it will relieve your pain and put you in a deep sleep.We very happy our purchase! Thank you again Massage Chair Relief!< /review>

< Text>
Massage Chair Relief: This is an outstanding company managed by the best people in the industry. Since I could not make it to the stores to test the chairs, Michael from the store in California took the time (almost 2 hours) to explain to me the difference between features and since this was my first purchase, he really had to be very detailed. I cannot remember the last time customer service was this good! Dr. Alan Weidner was there from the start and you will never feel that you are abandoned after you bought the chair. Overall, the company provides first class customer service and so far, I have not experienced anything better!

Titan Pro Executive: If you are a first time massage chair buyer, it is of your best interest to take every effort to try out the chair and take advantage of Dr. Alan's offer to visit his stores. I say this because you need to know how the chair functions when it is not broken or damaged. If I were to do it all over again, I would definitely do it.

It is a great chair just because it provides a comprehensive massage; from your feet to your shoulders, and if you want, the rollers will reach your head too. The chair allows you to customize the intensity and areas to be massaged. You can actually pin point an area of massage and using the manual feature, the chair will massage that particular area for you. For those who suffers from lower back pain, this feature is definitely a blessing! The zero gravity feature ( 2 positions) is a plus. The chair also accommodates you really well. The lower portion that houses your feet (ankle downwards) is actually movable so when you seat you can push this compartment with your legs and it moves to accommodate your height so that you, or anyone will seat naturally and comfortably. There are 5 programmed massage cycles and all of them are great. If you are planning to use the speakers, connect the chair via Bluetooth from your phone. It is pretty decent for a massage chair.

I stand at least 9 hours daily, 5 days a week due to the nature of my job. The Titan Pro Executive has alleviated all the pain and stiffness associated with this prolonged standing. My lower back pain is gone and on top of that I was able to exercise 5 days a week! I have lost 10 lbs due to this new "freedom". If you're having back pain for whatever reason and this pain has prohibited you from leading an active lifestyle, you should pay Michael a visit and try all the chairs. He should be able to help you decide which chair is good for you.

Yes, the chair will not cost you 500.00 but you can't put a price tag on your health and well-being, can you?

Unfortunately, the manual needs to be redone; seriously.

White Glove Service: I did not have the a good experience with the WGS. The chair was really delayed but as I had written above, Dr. Weidner intervened and the issue was resolved. Titan really needs to step up and copy Dr. Alan Weidner's commitment to his customers.

Overall, the Titan Pro Executive will provide you a very relaxing and deep tissue massage. It is worth the price.< /Text>

< review>
The place is a little tricky to find if you speed past it. Otherwise after the first time you've found it, it's easy to remember to slow down and make your turn. The layout is really weird, but I do enjoy using the cardio and machine rooms. The ladies restroom/lockers, sinks, toilets, whirlpool aren't just as updated as most people like it to be. It's gross and old looking but I never use them so I could care less. However the pool is a great plus! I just wish Fitness Evo gyms opened a little longer on the weekends. Overall, the staff up at the front is always greeting people and saying their good-byes. Other F.E. gyms the staff usually stays in one place and talks -- when you go up to them they look at you really rude as if you're interrupting their conversation which I think is highly unprofessional. The machines and free weights are clean, hardly any of them are broken which I think is good. I would recommend this gym for students who go to Fresno City college because it's just down the street! You can literally go to the gym in less than 5 mins, workout, and get back to school grounds within 5 mins. Or if you wanted to take a dip in the pool, then by all means! The pool would be nice to have more shade but that's just me being picky. I would come again! (Which I have been)</review>

Everyone was nice, we were seated super fast and were served drinks within minutes of settling in.  I loved that they had a vegan option and I opted for that (the vegan burger).  It was SO good, super flavorful and filling, on the best pretzel bun I‚Äôve ever had. It reheated well too, which I think says a lot about the integrity of a burger- especially a vegan one.  I would for sure go back!<//Text>

I was astonished to stop in to pick up my fairly regular cornbread app and Local Greens salad with salmon. While I waited for my order, I decided to grab a beer. The bartender was quite familiar - at first I thought she was pulling double duty and also worked somewhere else. Turns out I had seen her before not in a local bar but on my DVR - It was Lisa Marie from Bar Rescue! She was incredibly sweet and kind. Everyone should visit and say hi. I didn't want to bother her but she was more than happy to take a picture! Great decision on hiring her Union Kitchen & Tap - she's a good one. (Fully vaccinated FYI).< /Text>

<Rating>5</Rating><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOK-SnS23NUKNfdZoLUoFYyotQViIwb4WrtxQQ2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNWRjaUhgnVHUFtPLGoWTej37P0AkdpjgRTs9kU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMyXE4KUhyVpA45GNMNldgUeDnZSTG67cbIhr-7=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO2fjIXinAFO--4xwnPMvXGUwe0t9VDAUS7vznj=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMKl0wJOG8Jq4w4jYpKx0EtGkOmFeZradHup8w4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP6LV2qewfBCx4ESLHVt1cfe5vEZogm8uOPazSN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< Text>
At first sight, it doesn't look family friendly. But once seated at a table, we were very comfy with our 3 young kids. The kids menu is typical, but the food far exceeds expectations. Kids pasta is al dente and the sauce tastes fresh. I ordered a Mexican Mary brunch cocktail and it was spicy and bright with lime. My gumbo was spicy too-keepin it real! Oh that sauce was shiny and smooth and rich. Hubby got the brioche with egg and pork belly and his plate was licked clean. I highly recommend this place for families or couples or whatever.
One single constructive criticism tho- the beignets were too dense- one of them was still raw dough in the center. I wanted them so bad to be light pillows with powdered sugar like du monde. Alas, no dice. Still really live it here!<//Text>

<username>Taryn Shorr</username>< Text>
We came in on a Friday evening strictly for cocktails and, while the drinks were great, unfortunately we had horrible service. This is totally our type of place and we wanted to love it, but the service left a bad taste in our mouths. Every aspect was unreasonably slow - waiting to be greeted, waiting on our drinks, waiting to close the check. Neighboring tables were complaining about the same thing. This was early on a Friday when they were not particularly busy.

On the plus side, the cocktails are unique and well-made (and have cheeky names!), the space is really cool, and the patio is dog friendly.</Text>

<time>1496868567874<//time><review>Feels like a meet market. Maybe just because it's a hardwood restaurant-bar with tennis and ESPN on in the background. But since this is Encinitas, it's all-ages: Age is just a number. You don't feel old here, even if you're closer to 50 than 25. My lover and I come here when in town from fancier, crazier Las Vegas. We take seats in Union's big open windows, overlooking the little road. The flatbread is good. The salmon on salad chunk is better. Servers smile. Food comes quick. Spicy bloody Marys are exquisite. I'm saying that as a former New Orleans boy. The spicy Bloody Marys are missing the okra garden of Cajun sisters, but otherwise, these ones are choice. Four stars because the food is bar/restaurant 4/5. But if you are single, I imagine you'd 5 this place, as well as the Eve hippie fun cafe down the street, plus the low-rent Taco Stand covered patio not far away. @vegasanonymous</review>< Name>
Dougable Elfman</Name>

<username>Scott Woodruff<//username>< Date>
1515019428322<//Date>
<rating>5< /rating><Text>Union is a solid bar with great food, an extensive beer, wine and cocktail menu and friendly staff. There's bar/lounge seating options with full sit down dining as well. Located south of the heart of Encinitas, it's a good location with plenty of road parking to be found.
They have some of the BEST dry rub wings, with all sauces on the side so you can dip crispy wings into whatever sauce you fancy--please make sure you try these when you come here.
The curried muscles compliment the wings in a great way as they are tender with a hint of spice as well. Hiding in the curry sauce is sausage as well which is a nice surprise.
It's worth noting that I had an incident where a drunken customer was harassing me for no reason while I was sitting at the bar watching football. I ignored him, but he persisted. The management was quick to pull him aside and talk to him without making a scene, and handled it very well on all ends.</Text>< pictures>

< review>
This place is always busy, which is good. It's our second time at Union Kitchen & Tap. We visited a while ago when they first opened and the patio wasn't even ready yet.
It's in great location South Coast Hwy 101, Encinitas. Husband and I ordered handcrafted burgers: Colorado Bison, caramelized onion, garlic Aioli, Aged NY white cheddar, and brioche bun. Mine was the Union Burger, Brandt beef all natural half pound patty, tomato jam, cherrywood smoked bacon, aged NY white cheddar, brioche bun. Served with house fries to drink: pineapple juice and iced tea.
In general everything was very good our waitress Jennifer was friendly and fast.
The was no wait, bar was full of all types and ages of people. It's loud and dog friendly too.
The price for burgers are reasonable, would definitely go back to try the breakfast menu.< /review>

<user_id>109815267831202318650< /user_id><Response>None<//Response><Review>Looks like my review a year and a half ago was actually read. If your going to have Kennebec fries, you have to make poutine. That's like eating and slice of NY pizza with a  fork and knife. The poutine was good, but where was the gravy? The fries were a little big kind of like Bosscat in Costa Mesa, but still Kennebec and started off so well with the cheese perfectly melted. A solid dish and intro into poutine if you haven't been north of the border for the real thing

Ok so back to the rest of things. The steaks, though not USDA prime, was good. I ordered rare, and it came medium rare. I also would have preferred the butter topping to be unflavored. Jugs of beer are just pitchers. They are actually a good deal and the best way to drink here as they just seem understaffed, like everywhere and like all the time so don't expect to order a drink, pound it and not wait 15 minutes for them to come back around.

I recall the menu being bigger and the beer list being expansive. I as looking at entr√©es and actually thought I should just get 3 appetizers there just weren't the options I remember or expected. Burgers are still solid, they need more sauces and things to dip in them. Mac & Cheese is ok, aside from it needing to be creamier, I found the pasta itself a little firm. You have to ask for water, they will not offer and probably won't refill it for a while

Cocktails are still good and they really try not to pack the place until the kitchen closes, then it's a free for all club. I really think that once dinner is done they should shut off the TV's otherwise what's the point. The price point here is starting to rise, losing some of it's value. It's causing me to not think of them when deciding to get a drink in Encinitas.

Nothing has really improved over the years, but it's still a good place to come.
Ideally this would be a great place to grab a beer after work, but just 1 or 2 drinks max. The crowd here is a mix of beachy hipsters and yuppy suits. The beer and wine menu were about what I expected for a gastropub and I actually found the slew of big screen TV's to not take away from the pubbishness with a sports bars motif. Tall hardwood tables and chairs and the tall roll up doors make it very open and inviting. Summertime will be crowded for window stools. Nice bathroom, but could be larger, a healthy spirts selection. I got exactly 1 oz of whiskey when I asked for bulleit neat, which I thought was skimping it, I should have ordered 3 fingers (we all know that isn't accurate anymore, especially with the heavy weighted modern glasses). It was probably more surprising to me to see what 1 oz of liquor actually is. I normally don't order such a small amount.

I was a little disappointed in the menu. The burger was ok. I love the fact they use Kennebec fries, but they don't offer poutin, which is a killer dish and a good one can rival Carne Asada fries (and I'm from San Diego too). Duck leg and confit are a little too fine dining to go with beer and I felt a little out of place. The beet salad was excellent, but could due without the walnuts due to the sweetness of the beets and the fennel/star anise combo could have been balanced with a citrus/vinegar or red onion versus arugula. The fries were amazing, crisp and Kennebec stay that way for a while and don't get soggy like most. Chicken pesto flat bread was good. I wasn't a fan of the tomato's, they might have been stewed or blanched and not fresh crushed. Heavy grain/flour on the bottom got messy if you ate with your hands. I was really expecting more of an amalgamation of dishes and ideas. Nothing stood out as unique and it didn't quite seem artisanal or a seasonal daily menu. I really didn't see the creativity I expect from a gastropub, but then again I find a difference in that a true gastropub people come equally for food and libations, not fine dining around a bunch of drunks.<//Review><date>1450233571148<//date><Rating>3<//Rating><name>Walter Macalma<//name>< gmap_id>

<UserId.>117678678800840917917<//UserId.><username>VanAwesome< /username><Time>1389811009867<//Time><Rate>5< /Rate><Text>SHRIMP AND GRITS HOLY GOD!

This place is another peice of the puzzle as to why I love Encinitas so much.  You've got awesome oldschool, small town cafe's like The Encinitas Cafe, and then you have fantastic new-american places like this.

Now I've been to South Carolina, and tried the Shrimp and Grits of a James Beard award winning chef, and let me tell you something right now, the Shrimp and Grits at Union Kitchen, DESTROY ALL COMPETITION.   It's one of my favorite dishes that I've ever had.  I've been back probably 15 times and I've never even thought about ordering anything else.

I'm sure the rest of the food is good, but I just can't bring myself to not order possibly the best S&G's on the face of the earth.

Now I'm actually on a diet right now, and don't allow myself to eat things like Grits, but as soon as I reach my goal weight, I'll be back, and I will Chomp the b'jesus out of it once again.

Bless you Union.  Bless your heart.</Text>< Pics>
